448","1380–1425":"1380–1425","1473":"1473","1482":"1482","1380":"1380","1448":"1448","1415":"1415","1404":"1404","1425":"1425","before 22 January 1448":"before 22 January 1448","1479":"1479","1413":"1413","1402":"1402","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1411":"1411","1400":"1400","1398":"1398","1430":"1430","1419":"1419","1407":"1407","1417":"1417","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wortley, Yorkshire, England":"Wortley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wortley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Wortley in Tankersley (Yorkshire), or Lower, Upper, or New Wortley in Armley (Yorkshire), or (least likely) Wortley in Wotton under Edge (Gloucestershire). The place in Tankersley derives from Old English <i>wyrt</i> ‘plant, vegetable’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The place in Armley derives from an Old English personal name <i>Wyrca</i> or <i>Weorca</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i>. The Gloucestershire placename derives from Old English <i>wyrt</i> + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Worley","meanings":["English:","habitational name with different origins. In the West Midlands this surname is most probably derived from Great or Little Wyrley in Norton Canes (Staffordshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>wīr</i> ‘bog myrtle’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. In the East Midlands, the name is possibly from Worlick in Ramsey (Huntingdonshire), the etymology of the which is uncertain. In northern England, possibly from Whirley in Over Alderley (Cheshire), which has the same etymology as the Staffordshire names. There may also be a further unlocated source of this habitational name in southern England.","possibly an irregular variant of   Wortley   or   Warley  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":32,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Wortley was born in 1423, in Wortley, Yorkshire, England, her father, Nicholas Wortley I, was 46 and her mother, Elizabeth Waterton, was 43. She had at least 1 daughter with Roger Bolton. She died in 1473, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1423–1473":"1423–1473","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1402–Male":"1402–Surnud","1404–Male":"1404–Surnud","1407–Female":"1407–Surnud","14